export const PROMPT_COACH_SKILL = "---\nname: legal-prompt-coach\ndescription: >\n  Guide for optimising prompts and instructions for legal work with AI tools.\n  This skill should be used when the user asks to \"write a prompt\", \"optimise a prompt\",\n  \"coach me on prompting\", \"help me prompt Claude/Copilot/ChatGPT for legal work\",\n  \"create instructions for contract review\", \"build a prompt for risk analysis\",\n  or is drafting instructions intended for an AI assistant to perform legal tasks\n  such as review, analysis, gap analysis, risk matrices, summaries, or stakeholder communications.\nversion: 0.2.0\n---\n\n# Legal Prompt Coach\n\nTransform rough descriptions or initial prompts into structured, high-performance instructions for AI-assisted legal work. Optimised for Claude, with adaptation support for Copilot and ChatGPT.\n\n## Prompt Complexity Scaling\n\nNot every task needs the full treatment. Match the prompt structure to the task complexity:\n\n| Level | When to Use | Structure | Example |\n|---|---|---|---|\n| **Lightweight** (2-part) | Simple, low-stakes, single-step tasks | Task + Output | Quick internal email, simple question, status update |\n| **Standard** (4-part) | Most day-to-day legal work | Role + Task + Output + Constraints | Stakeholder email, contract clause query, briefing note |\n| **Heavy** (full 6-part) | Complex, high-stakes, multi-faceted analysis | All 6 parts + examples | Contract review, risk matrix, DD, gap analysis, board paper |\n| **Chained** (multi-prompt) | Very complex tasks, long documents, multi-lens analysis | Multiple prompts in sequence | Full DD workstream, large contract negotiation prep |\n\n**Rule of thumb:** If the task takes you more than 30 minutes manually, it probably needs Standard or Heavy. If it takes a full day, consider Chained.\n\n## Core Prompt Architecture\n\nEvery legal prompt draws from this 6-part structure. Scale to complexity \u2014 not every section is needed for every task.\n\n### 1. Role & Context Frame\n\nSet the AI's expertise level and perspective.\n\n**Pattern:**\n```\nYou are a senior [specialisation] lawyer with [X] years of experience in [jurisdiction].\nYou are advising [audience context \u2014 e.g. in-house counsel, commercial team, board].\n```\n\n**Why it matters:** Role framing activates domain-specific reasoning. A \"senior commercial lawyer advising in-house counsel at a global advertising group\" will flag different risks than a \"regulatory compliance specialist advising a tech startup.\"\n\n**Calibration:**\n- Match the role to the task (don't use \"litigation partner\" for a procurement review)\n- Include jurisdiction when it matters (AU, US, UK, multi-jurisdictional)\n- Specify the advisory relationship (advising internal legal, advising business, advising external client)\n- For Publicis work: \"advising in-house counsel at a global advertising and communications group\" anchors the right perspective\n\n### 2. Task Definition\n\nState exactly what the AI should do, in imperative form. Be surgical \u2014 one primary task per prompt.\n\n**Weak:** \"Look at this contract and tell me what you think.\"\n**Strong:** \"Review this Master Services Agreement against our standard media services terms. Identify every clause that deviates from our preferred position. For each deviation, classify the risk as High/Medium/Low and provide a recommended redline.\"\n\n**Key principles:**\n- One primary task per prompt (chain if needed \u2014 see `references/chaining-guide.md`)\n- Use active verbs: Review, Analyse, Identify, Draft, Compare, Summarise, Assess, Flag, Recommend\n- Specify the analytical framework upfront if there is one\n- Avoid common anti-patterns \u2014 see `references/anti-patterns.md`\n\n### 3. Input Specification\n\nTell the AI exactly what materials it's working with and what to pay attention to.\n\n**Pattern:**\n```\nMaterials provided:\n- [Document name] \u2014 [what it is, what version, key context]\n- [Reference document] \u2014 [how it relates]\n\nFocus areas: [specific clauses, sections, or issues to prioritise]\nIgnore: [anything explicitly out of scope]\n```\n\n**Never silently attach a document** without describing what it is, who the parties are, and what the commercial context is.\n\n### 4. Analytical Framework\n\nFor complex tasks, provide the reasoning structure.\n\n**Common legal frameworks:**\n- Risk matrix (severity \u00d7 likelihood, 1-5 scale)\n- Traffic light (Red/Amber/Green with defined thresholds)\n- Deviation analysis (Accept / Negotiate / Escalate / Reject)\n- Gap analysis (required vs. present, with severity)\n- Compliance checklist (regulatory requirements vs. current state)\n- IRAC (Issue, Rule, Application, Conclusion \u2014 for research memos)\n\n### 5. Output Format\n\nSpecify exactly what the output should look like, including audience calibration.\n\n**Pattern:**\n```\nStructure your response as follows:\n1. Executive Summary (3-5 sentences, suitable for [audience])\n2. [Main analysis \u2014 table, numbered findings, etc.]\n3. Recommendations (prioritised, actionable)\n```\n\n**Critical:** Always include a brief example of what good output looks like for the main analysis section. Even one example row/entry dramatically improves quality. See template library for examples.\n\n### 6. Constraints & Guardrails\n\nSet boundaries. Include what NOT to do.\n\n**Standard defaults** (include in most prompts):\n```\n- Use Australian English spelling and conventions\n- Do not provide formal legal advice \u2014 frame as analysis and observations\n- Flag any areas where insufficient information limits the assessment\n- If a provision is ambiguous, note the ambiguity rather than assuming an interpretation\n- Acknowledge this is AI-assisted analysis where appropriate\n```\n\n**Task-specific constraints:** length limits, scope boundaries, assumptions to make or avoid, audience-specific language requirements.\n\n## Platform-Specific Optimisation\n\n### Claude (Primary)\n\nClaude responds best to:\n- **XML tags** for structured sections: `<role>`, `<task>`, `<context>`, `<format>`, `<constraints>`\n- **Examples** in `<example>` tags \u2014 even brief ones dramatically improve quality\n- **Extended thinking** for complex multi-issue analysis\n- **Negative constraints** stated clearly: \"Do NOT summarise the entire agreement \u2014 focus only on deviations\"\n- **Long documents:** Claude handles these well natively \u2014 don't artificially chunk unless necessary\n\n### Copilot (M365)\n\nCopilot operates within the Microsoft 365 ecosystem, which gives it different strengths and constraints:\n\n**Strengths:**\n- Native access to documents open in Word, Excel, PowerPoint \u2014 no need to attach or paste\n- Can reference SharePoint/OneDrive files by name\n- In-document editing: can draft directly into Word, create tables in Excel, build slides\n- Good for: quick in-situ edits, summarising open documents, drafting within existing templates, reformatting\n\n**Limitations:**\n- Shorter effective context window \u2014 long, detailed prompts degrade performance\n- Weaker at complex multi-step analytical chains\n- No XML tags \u2014 use markdown headers and inline structure\n- Less controllable output format \u2014 tends to override format instructions with its own preferences\n- Reference documents must be accessible in M365 (SharePoint/OneDrive/open in app)\n\n**Optimisation patterns for Copilot:**\n- Keep prompts under ~500 words. Front-load the most important instruction.\n- Use the pattern: \"In this document, [task]. Focus on [specific sections]. Present as [format].\"\n- For contract review in Word: \"Review this document and add comments to any clause that [criteria]\" works well as it leverages Copilot's native commenting ability\n- For data extraction: Copilot \u2192 Excel is strong. \"Create a table from this document listing [fields]\"\n- Role framing: 1 sentence max. \"As a commercial lawyer reviewing this agreement, [task].\"\n- Step numbering for multi-step tasks (but keep to 3-4 steps max)\n- When quality matters more than convenience: draft the prompt in Claude, paste the optimised output into the relevant M365 app\n\n**When to use Copilot vs Claude:**\n| Use Copilot when... | Use Claude when... |\n|---|---|\n| Quick edits within an open document | Deep analytical review |\n| Summarising a document open in Word | Complex multi-issue risk assessment |\n| Extracting data into Excel | Detailed contract markup with reasoning |\n| Drafting within existing templates | Crafting nuanced stakeholder communications |\n| Fast, good-enough first pass | High-stakes analysis requiring precision |\n\n### ChatGPT\n\nAdapt prompts for ChatGPT by:\n- **System message** for role and persistent constraints (separate from user message)\n- Clear user message with the task and materials\n- Bullet-point output instructions rather than XML-tagged\n- More explicit guardrails: \"If you are unsure about any legal position, say so explicitly. Do not fabricate case references or statutory citations.\"\n- For recurring workflows: consider Custom GPT configuration\n- Consider Projects for persistent context across conversations\n\n## Context Window Management\n\nFor long documents and large analytical tasks:\n\n**Front-load critical context.** Place the most important information (task, key issues, comparison points) before the document text, not after. AI attention is strongest at the beginning and end of the context.\n\n**Signal document structure.** \"The attached is a 45-page MSA. Key sections for this review: clause 8 (Liability), clause 12 (IP), clause 15 (Termination). Other clauses may be relevant but these are priority.\"\n\n**Targeted extraction over full review.** For very long documents, consider: \"Extract and list all clauses related to [topic]\" as a first pass, then deep-dive on the extracted clauses. This is more reliable than asking for a full-document review.\n\n**Summarise before deep-diving.** For data rooms or multi-document reviews: \"First, provide a 1-sentence summary of each document. Then I'll tell you which to analyse in detail.\"\n\n**Watch for context fatigue.** AI analysis quality tends to degrade in the second half of very long documents. If you notice the back half of a contract getting less attention, split the review into two passes.\n\n## Coaching Workflow\n\nWhen coaching a user on their prompt, follow this process:\n\n### 1. Understand Intent\nWhat legal task? What deliverable? Who's the audience? Which platform?\n\n### 2. Assess the Draft \u2014 Scoring Rubric\n\nScore each element as Weak / Adequate / Strong:\n\n| Element | Weak | Adequate | Strong |\n|---|---|---|---|\n| **Role** | Generic (\"a lawyer\") or missing | Specialisation stated but no jurisdiction or advisory context | Specific specialisation + jurisdiction + advisory relationship |\n| **Task** | Vague or multi-task (\"review and advise\") | Clear primary task but could be interpreted two ways | Single unambiguous imperative with active verb |\n| **Input** | Document attached with no description | Document described but no focus areas | Full description, focus areas, scope boundaries, context |\n| **Framework** | No framework \u2014 AI left to guess | Framework named but not defined (\"use a risk matrix\") | Framework specified with scales, thresholds, and definitions |\n| **Output** | No format specified | Structure requested but no example | Explicit structure + example of desired output |\n| **Constraints** | None | Basic constraints (language, length) | Comprehensive: tone, audience, what NOT to do, assumptions, caveats |\n\n**Scoring guide:**\n- 0-1 Strong elements \u2192 Needs significant rework\n- 2-3 Strong elements \u2192 Good foundation, targeted improvements\n- 4-6 Strong elements \u2192 Minor refinements only\n\n### 3. Enhance\nRewrite with proper structure, adding missing elements. Flag assumptions.\n\n### 4. Explain Changes\nBrief annotation of what was improved and WHY each change matters.\n\n### 5. Offer Variants\nIf the task could benefit from a different approach (chaining, different framework, different output format), suggest it.\n\n## Reference Library\n\n| Resource | What it Contains | When to Read |\n|---|---|---|\n| `references/templates.md` | 15 battle-tested prompt templates with few-shot examples | User wants a template or a starting scaffold |\n| `references/cheat-sheet.md` | Quick reference: structure, verbs, frameworks, platform comparison | Quick lookup during coaching |\n| `references/chaining-guide.md` | When and how to decompose complex tasks into prompt chains | Task is complex or involves long documents |\n| `references/anti-patterns.md` | Top 10 common mistakes and how to fix them | Diagnosing why a prompt produced bad output |\n| `references/iteration-guide.md` | How to troubleshoot and refine prompts iteratively | Output isn't right and user needs to diagnose why |\n| `references/publicis-conventions.md` | Publicis Groupe standard positions, terminology, conventions | Prompts involving Publicis legal work |\n| `references/validation-checklist.md` | How to verify AI-generated legal output | Before relying on or sharing AI output |\n";

